<li id="cite_note-ar4_uncertainty-102"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ar4_uncertainty_102-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ar4_uncertainty_102-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ar4_uncertainty_102-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ar4_uncertainty_102-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">In the IPCC Fourth Assessment Report, the following scale is used to quantify uncertainty: "virtually certain" &gt;99%; "extremely likely" &gt;95%; "very likely" &gt;90%; "likely" &gt;66%; "more likely than not" &gt;50%; "about as likely as not" 33 to 66%; "unlikely" &lt;33%; "very unlikely" &lt;10%; "extremely unlikely" &lt;5%; "exceptionally unlikely" &lt;1%. <cite id="CITEREFSolomon,_S." class="citation cs2">Solomon, S.; et&#160;al., <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ipcc.ch/publications_and_data/ar4/wg1/en/tssts-2.html">"Box TS.1: Treatment of Uncertainties in the Working Group I Assessment"</a>, <i>Technical Summary</i>, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120612142856/http://www.ipcc.ch/publications_and_data/ar4/wg1/en/tssts-2.html">archived</a> from the original on 12 June 2012<span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">18 August</span> 2012</span></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Box+TS.1%3A+Treatment+of+Uncertainties+in+the+Working+Group+I+Assessment&amp;rft.btitle=Technical+Summary&amp;rft.au=Solomon%2C+S.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ipcc.ch%2Fpublications_and_data%2Far4%2Fwg1%2Fen%2Ftssts-2.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+climate+change+science" class="Z3988"></span>, in <a href="#CITEREFIPCC_AR4_WG12007">IPCC AR4 WG1 2007</a>.</span>
</li>
